Introduction: Our story & Amazon ML service of choise

As students interested in the intersection of the financial markets and the data science world, we are eager to apply analytical and scholarly approaches to finance.

As a group:

we are particularly fascinated by the financial markets in the last century and want to explore topics such as the historical returns of stock and bond markets during the recession days of 1930s (many researchers omit data from the Great Depression and the second world war to start the analysis in the 1950s). As the global financial market of today undergoes many unprecedented challenges, we want to go back to history and see if any lessons can be discovered.

However, many reports and research back then are not digitized but only available in hard copies of books, newspapers, and other printouts, and it is a demanding process to manually input all the data to digital data frames that computers today can understand.

Personal experience and applications:

Amy - From working as a Treasury intern at Inspire Brands, I realized that many businesses are working to move their current databases to an online, automated platform rather than manual inputting of data from files. This past summer, I experimented with extracting data from digital files and automatically inputting them into an xlsx. formatted file through Power Query in Excel, as well as Python. However, after further research, I learned that the AWS Textract program may significantly optimize the process of extracting data from a physical source and can eliminate the need of manual input of data. Its capability to pinpoint multiple files in one location and extract it makes it extremely powerful in the work setting moving forward.

Group Research:

Furthermore, one of the metrics that attracted our attention during the literature review is Total Factor Productivity (TFP).

Furthermore, one of the metrics that attracted our attention during the literature review is Total Factor Productivity (TFP).

  • TFP, also called multi-factor productivity, which is usually measured as the ratio of aggregate output (e.g., GDP) to aggregate inputs. It is a measure of productive efficiency in that it measures how much output can be produced from a certain amount of inputs.

  • Many researchers use this metric to compare productivity efficiency across different economies and individual companies.

  • We came across a research paper by Oum and Yu that finds that the major European carriers and the carriers in newly industrialized countries in Asia have achieved significantly higher productivity growth than their North American counterparts during 19861993. The citation of the paper is attached below:

Tae Hoon Oum, Chunyan Yu, A productivity comparison of the world's major airlines, Journal of Air Transport Management, Volume 2, Issues 34,1995, Pages 181-195, ISSN 0969-6997, https://doi.org/10.1016/0969-6997(96)00007-5.

  • Intrigued by this literature, we wonder how does the TFP data look like for American airlines. Accordingly, we narrowed down our data selection and chose a Fed Reserve Bank disclosed TFP decomposition by airline companies as a primary sample to evaluate the performance of Textract.

  • Another recource we utilized was on the O'Reilly learning platform, which showed real world case studies of Textract in similar contexts. The reading provided us with a deeper understanding of Textract's features and techniques that guided our approach in analyzing our financial documents.The citation of the site is attached below:

M, Mona, and Premkumar Rangarajan. Natural Language Processing with AWS AI Services. OReilly Online Learning, Packt Publishing, www.oreilly.com/library/view/natural-language-processing/9781801812535/B17528_02_Final_SB_ePub.xhtml. Accessed 29 Nov. 2023.

Therefore, we choose to work with Amazon Textract ML service , which can scan the input file, extract the text information, and output as a csv file.

Data Analysis: Testing the accuracy of Textract by image resolution and complexity

During our data collection process, we noticed that the quality of the image will be different depending on the type of scanning technique deployed, which led us wonder if Textract can do equally well if the image is blurry.

We believe that it is harder for Textract to perform as the image gets more blurry, and we set out to test it by adding fuzziness to our data and reapply the Textract function. Intuitively, we expect to see an obvious linearly decreasing trend in the outcome confidence level as the blurriness increases.

Building on this intuitive hypothesis, we also wonder how much less accurate / confident the funcationality will be as image resolution worsens, which is later discussed in the mismatch percentage exercise.

Blurring the image

To begin with, let's find one image as an example.

In [ ]:

Then, we blur the image from 0 to 6 degree.

In [ ]:
from PIL import Image, ImageFilter
folder_path = 'blurry-images'

if os.path.exists(folder_path):
    # If it exists, remove the folder and its contents
    shutil.rmtree(folder_path)

os.makedirs(folder_path, exist_ok=True)

degree=np.linspace(0,6,16)

for i in degree:
    blur_im=im.filter(ImageFilter.BoxBlur(i))
    imname='blur'+f'{i}'+'_im.JPG'
    image_path = os.path.join(folder_path, imname)
    blur_im.save(image_path)

Then, we will apply the Textract service on the images with varying degree of blurriness.

Note that Textract has a quality that returns both the text and the confidence level of its detection, and we will utilize the confidence level to conduct further analysis by calculateing the average confidence interval for cells detection.

In [ ]:
import os
import boto3
import numpy as np
from scipy import stats
import pandas as pd
import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings('ignore')


# Create a Textract client
client = boto3.client('textract')

# Specify the folder containing images
image_folder = 'blurry-images'

# DataFrame to store results
results_df = pd.DataFrame(columns=['Image', 'Mean Confidence', 'Confidence Interval'])

# Iterate through each image in the folder
for filename in os.listdir(image_folder):
    if filename.endswith(".jpg") or filename.endswith(".JPG"):  # Adjust file extensions as needed
        image_path = os.path.join(image_folder, filename)

        # Read the image as bytes
        with open(image_path, 'rb') as image_file:
            image_bytes = image_file.read()

        # Call Textract's analyze_document API
        response = client.analyze_document(Document={'Bytes': image_bytes}, FeatureTypes=['TABLES'])

        # Process the response and extract confidence values
        confidence_values = [block['Confidence'] for block in response['Blocks'] if block['BlockType'] == 'CELL']

        # Calculate confidence interval
        confidence_interval = stats.t.interval(0.95, len(confidence_values)-1, loc=np.mean(confidence_values), scale=stats.sem(confidence_values))

        # Save results to DataFrame
        results_df = results_df.append({
            'Image': filename,
            'Mean Confidence': np.mean(confidence_values),
            'Confidence Interval': confidence_interval
        }, ignore_index=True)

# Print or save the DataFrame as needed
print(results_df)
# results_df.to_csv('confidence_results.csv', index=False)  # Uncomment to save to a CSV file

plt.show()

From the chart, we can see clearly the general trend that the more blurry the image is, the less confidence there is for the Textract outcome. Nevertheless, despite the clearest image has the highest mean confidence level (as expected), the blurries image is not the lowest ranked observation by outcome confidence level, as observations with blurriness around 5 to 5.5 give even less confidence than the observation wuth blurry level 6.

Despite the zig-zag shape of the mean confidence level trend line, since the confidence intervals mostly overlap with each other, we can conclude that the relationship between blurry degree and outcome confidence level is linearly decreasing.

Extract the table from Nonblurry image

Next, we want to compare the extracted content of the text by cell and see the mismatch rate between the original image and the blurry ones.

To begin with, we prepare the extracted table for the scanned image using Textract, and we do so for both the original image and the blurred image respectively.

# functions for extracting and printing tables in Python
def map_blocks(blocks, block_type):
    return {
        block['Id']: block
        for block in blocks
        if block['BlockType'] == block_type
    }

blocks = response['Blocks']
tables = map_blocks(blocks, 'TABLE')
cells = map_blocks(blocks, 'CELL')
words = map_blocks(blocks, 'WORD')
selections = map_blocks(blocks, 'SELECTION_ELEMENT')
In [ ]:
def get_children_ids(block):
    for rels in block.get('Relationships', []):
        if rels['Type'] == 'CHILD':
            yield from rels['Ids']
  • Run a loop structure to extract each cell in the table:
In [ ]:
import pandas as pd

dataframes = []

for table in tables.values():

    # Determine all the cells that belong to this table
    table_cells = [cells[cell_id] for cell_id in get_children_ids(table)]

    # Determine the table's number of rows and columns
    n_rows = max(cell['RowIndex'] for cell in table_cells)
    n_cols = max(cell['ColumnIndex'] for cell in table_cells)
    content = [[None for _ in range(n_cols)] for _ in range(n_rows)]

    # Fill in each cell
    for cell in table_cells:
        cell_contents = [
            words[child_id]['Text']
            if child_id in words
            else selections[child_id]['SelectionStatus']
            for child_id in get_children_ids(cell)
        ]
        i = cell['RowIndex'] - 1
        j = cell['ColumnIndex'] - 1
        content[i][j] = ' '.join(cell_contents)

    # We assume that the first row corresponds to the column names
    dataframe = pd.DataFrame(content[1:], columns=content[0])
    dataframes.append(dataframe)

scanned_blur=[]
image_folder = 'blurry-images/'
for files in os.listdir(image_folder):
    if files == ".ipynb_checkpoints":
        continue
    image_path=image_folder+f'{files}'
    im = Image.open(image_path)
    buffered = io.BytesIO()
    im.save(buffered, format='PNG')
    client = boto3.client('textract')
    response = client.analyze_document(Document={'Bytes': buffered.getvalue()},FeatureTypes=['TABLES'])

    def map_blocks(blocks, block_type):
        return {block['Id']: block for block in blocks if block['BlockType'] == block_type}
    blocks = response['Blocks']
    tables = map_blocks(blocks, 'TABLE')
    cells = map_blocks(blocks, 'CELL')
    words = map_blocks(blocks, 'WORD')
    selections = map_blocks(blocks, 'SELECTION_ELEMENT')

    def get_children_ids(block):
        for rels in block.get('Relationships', []):
            if rels['Type'] == 'CHILD':
                yield from rels['Ids']

    dataframes=[]

    for table in tables.values():

        # Determine all the cells that belong to this table
        table_cells = [cells[cell_id] for cell_id in get_children_ids(table)]

        # Determine the table's number of rows and columns
        n_rows = max(cell['RowIndex'] for cell in table_cells)
        n_cols = max(cell['ColumnIndex'] for cell in table_cells)
        content = [[None for _ in range(n_cols)] for _ in range(n_rows)]

        # Fill in each cell
        for cell in table_cells:
            cell_contents = [
                words[child_id]['Text']
                if child_id in words
                else selections[child_id]['SelectionStatus']
                for child_id in get_children_ids(cell)
            ]
            i = cell['RowIndex'] - 1
            j = cell['ColumnIndex'] - 1
            content[i][j] = ' '.join(cell_contents)

        # We assume that the first row corresponds to the column names
        dataframe = pd.DataFrame(content[1:], columns=content[0])
        dataframes.append(dataframe)
    scanned_blur.append(dataframes)

Finally, we compile all extracted dataframes into a list.

Here, we calculate the mismatched rate for each of the blurred images. This is a procedure to compare the content cell by cell, i.e., if the cell of the table from the blurred image contains different content than the same cell of the table from the original image, then we mark it as one instance of mismatch.

Intuitively, we expect the mismatch to be more frequent in images with higher blurriness.

In [ ]:
cell_comparison=pd.DataFrame()
mismatched=[]
percent_mis=[]
for i in range(len(degree)):
    # Compare the two DataFrames element-wise
    not_equal_mask = scanned_blur[i][0].ne(df_unblur)
    total=not_equal_mask.shape[0]*not_equal_mask.shape[1]
    # Count the number of cells that are not equal
    num_not_equal_cells = not_equal_mask.sum().sum()
    mismatched.append(num_not_equal_cells)
    percent_mis.append(num_not_equal_cells/total)

cell_comparison['mismatched cell']=sorted(mismatched)
cell_comparison['blurry']=degree
cell_comparison['percent mismatched']=sorted(percent_mis)
cell_comparison

This is the record of mismatch for all the 15 blurred images. We see that with blurry level from 0-2.8, there is a perfect match; then, starting from 3.2 level of blurriness, there starts to have mismatches, but only for a few cells; the mismatched cells start to grow significanltly as the blurry level passes 4.8, and about 90% of the cells are mismatched when the image is level-6 blurry,which represents a palpable misrepresentation of the data source.

We further visualize the relationship in a line chart below:

We can see that for degree 5 and 6, the image becomes so unclear that it is very hard to identify the text by eye. Therefore, it is reasonable that Textract performs less well in that case.

Admittedly, in daily usage and research work, we would not expect the input image resolution to be this poorly, and we can see that if the image is blurry from degree 0 to 3, the mismatch percentage is very close to zero. Therefore, we still feel comfortable about the validity of Textract and its normal use cases.

Double-column page with complex format and more data points

To take our analysis a step further, we wonder if Textract can uphold the accuracy level as the input data structure becomes more complex.

To test this question, we deliberately chose the below image. This picture contains return data for stock indexes worldwide, as well as a handful of individual stocks' performance data. We will replicate the same procedure with this sample to see if there is any identifiable difference in the outcome.

Then, we calculate the confidence interval and funnel the findings to a dataframe.

In [ ]:
import os
import boto3
import numpy as np
from scipy import stats
import pandas as pd
import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings('ignore')


# Create a Textract client
client = boto3.client('textract')

# Specify the folder containing images
image_folder = 'col-images'

# DataFrame to store results
results_df = pd.DataFrame(columns=['Image', 'Mean Confidence', 'Confidence Interval'])

# Iterate through each image in the folder
for filename in os.listdir(image_folder):
    if filename.endswith(".jpg") or filename.endswith(".JPG"):  # Adjust file extensions as needed
        image_path = os.path.join(image_folder, filename)

        # Read the image as bytes
        with open(image_path, 'rb') as image_file:
            image_bytes = image_file.read()

        # Call Textract's analyze_document API
        response = client.analyze_document(Document={'Bytes': image_bytes}, FeatureTypes=['TABLES'])

        # Process the response and extract confidence values
        confidence_values = [block['Confidence'] for block in response['Blocks'] if block['BlockType'] == 'CELL']

        # Calculate confidence interval
        confidence_interval = stats.t.interval(0.95, len(confidence_values)-1, loc=np.mean(confidence_values), scale=stats.sem(confidence_values))

        # Save results to DataFrame
        results_df = results_df.append({
            'Image': filename,
            'Mean Confidence': np.mean(confidence_values),
            'Confidence Interval': confidence_interval
        }, ignore_index=True)

# Print or save the DataFrame as needed
print(results_df)
# results_df.to_csv('confidence_results.csv', index=False)  # Uncomment to save to a CSV file

We can see that (1) Even for the original image, the mean confidence level is lower (84%) compared to the previous example (88%), which means for more complex data layout, the accuracy of Textract decreases even when the image resolution is kept constant; (2) The relationship is also generally negatively correlated, but we also noticed that the images with blurry level between 3 to 4 have less confidence level that those that are more blurry (5 to 6). While we are not completely sure about the factors that contribute to this phenomenon, we think it represents the variability in the Textract outcome.

# functions for extracting and printing tables in Python
def map_blocks(blocks, block_type):
    return {
        block['Id']: block
        for block in blocks
        if block['BlockType'] == block_type
    }

blocks = response['Blocks']
tables = map_blocks(blocks, 'TABLE')
cells = map_blocks(blocks, 'CELL')
words = map_blocks(blocks, 'WORD')
selections = map_blocks(blocks, 'SELECTION_ELEMENT')
In [ ]:
def get_children_ids(block):
    for rels in block.get('Relationships', []):
        if rels['Type'] == 'CHILD':
            yield from rels['Ids']
In [ ]:
import pandas as pd

dataframes = []

for table in tables.values():

    # Determine all the cells that belong to this table
    table_cells = [cells[cell_id] for cell_id in get_children_ids(table)]

    # Determine the table's number of rows and columns
    n_rows = max(cell['RowIndex'] for cell in table_cells)
    n_cols = max(cell['ColumnIndex'] for cell in table_cells)
    content = [[None for _ in range(n_cols)] for _ in range(n_rows)]

    # Fill in each cell
    for cell in table_cells:
        cell_contents = [
            words[child_id]['Text']
            if child_id in words
            else selections[child_id]['SelectionStatus']
            for child_id in get_children_ids(cell)
        ]
        i = cell['RowIndex'] - 1
        j = cell['ColumnIndex'] - 1
        content[i][j] = ' '.join(cell_contents)

    # We assume that the first row corresponds to the column names
    dataframe = pd.DataFrame(content[1:], columns=content[0])
    dataframes.append(dataframe)

scanned_blur=[]
image_folder = 'col-images/'
for files in os.listdir(image_folder):
    if files == ".ipynb_checkpoints":
        continue
    image_path=image_folder+f'{files}'
    im = Image.open(image_path)
    buffered = io.BytesIO()
    im.save(buffered, format='PNG')
    client = boto3.client('textract')
    response = client.analyze_document(Document={'Bytes': buffered.getvalue()},FeatureTypes=['TABLES'])

    def map_blocks(blocks, block_type):
        return {block['Id']: block for block in blocks if block['BlockType'] == block_type}
    blocks = response['Blocks']
    tables = map_blocks(blocks, 'TABLE')
    cells = map_blocks(blocks, 'CELL')
    words = map_blocks(blocks, 'WORD')
    selections = map_blocks(blocks, 'SELECTION_ELEMENT')

    def get_children_ids(block):
        for rels in block.get('Relationships', []):
            if rels['Type'] == 'CHILD':
                yield from rels['Ids']

    dataframes=[]

    for table in tables.values():

        # Determine all the cells that belong to this table
        table_cells = [cells[cell_id] for cell_id in get_children_ids(table)]

        # Determine the table's number of rows and columns
        n_rows = max(cell['RowIndex'] for cell in table_cells)
        n_cols = max(cell['ColumnIndex'] for cell in table_cells)
        content = [[None for _ in range(n_cols)] for _ in range(n_rows)]

        # Fill in each cell
        for cell in table_cells:
            cell_contents = [
                words[child_id]['Text']
                if child_id in words
                else selections[child_id]['SelectionStatus']
                for child_id in get_children_ids(cell)
            ]
            i = cell['RowIndex'] - 1
            j = cell['ColumnIndex'] - 1
            content[i][j] = ' '.join(cell_contents)

        # We assume that the first row corresponds to the column names
        dataframe = pd.DataFrame(content[1:], columns=content[0])
        dataframes.append(dataframe)
    scanned_blur.append(dataframes)

cell_comparison=pd.DataFrame()
mismatched=[]
percent_mis=[]
for i in range(len(degree)):
    # Compare the two DataFrames element-wise
    not_equal_mask = scanned_blur[i][0].ne(df_unblur)
    total=not_equal_mask.shape[0]*not_equal_mask.shape[1]
    # Count the number of cells that are not equal
    num_not_equal_cells = not_equal_mask.sum().sum()
    mismatched.append(num_not_equal_cells)
    percent_mis.append(num_not_equal_cells/total)

plt.figure(figsize=(20,20))

image_path1 = './col-images/col2.0_im.JPG'
image_path2 = './col-images/col4.0_im.JPG'
image_path3 = './col-images/col6.0_im.JPG'

# Load images using mpimg.imread
img1 = mpimg.imread(image_path1)
img2 = mpimg.imread(image_path2)
img3 = mpimg.imread(image_path3)

plt.subplot(1, 3, 1)
plt.imshow(img1)
plt.title('degree 2')

plt.subplot(1, 3, 2)
plt.imshow(img2)
plt.title('degree 4')

plt.subplot(1, 3, 3)
plt.imshow(img3)
plt.title('degree 6')

# Adjust layout to prevent overlapping titles
plt.tight_layout()

# Show the subplots
plt.show()

We can also see this with our eyes - when the image is level 2 blurred, we can still try to identify the content, but it becomes indecipherable when the blurry degree reaches 4, which is where the Textract outcome also becomes very inaccurate.

To conclude, we find that the accuracy level of Textract decreases as the input image layout gets more complicated. For more complex data sources, the input image needs to have higher resolution for the Textract output to be meaningful. When working with simpler data sources, there is a larger tolerance on the image quality for Textract to operate, but when the user is working with more compact and complicated data layout, they need to ensure decent image resolution to extract the content accurately.

Further Application: JSON values and ChatGPT

At the end, we include some further application of Textract, linking the use case to ChatGPT.

  • We can use chatGPT, by implementing OpenAI API in python, to help us adjust and customize the table before we finalize the extraction process and download the table.
  • ChatGPT has shown to be more efficient and accurate with JSON values, so we need to first convert the data frame into JSON key-pair values.
